definitions.definition: Near the end of a period of time.
examples: The seedlings appeared to be coming along nicely until a late frost killed them.

definitions.definition: Specifically, near the end of the day .
examples: It was getting late and I was tired.

definitions.definition: Associated with the end of a period.
examples: Late Latin is less fully inflected than classical Latin.

definitions.definition: Not arriving or occurring until after an expected time.
examples: The flowers were late in blooming because of the prolonged cold weather.
Panos was so late that he arrived at the meeting after Antonio, who had the excuse of being in hospital for most of the night.
The heavy snow made all the trains late .

definitions.definition: Levied as a surcharge on a payment which has not arrived by a specified deadline .
examples: The power company suspended late fees during the pandemic.

definitions.definition: Not having had an expected menstrual period .
examples: I'm late , honey. Could you buy a test ?

definitions.definition: Deceased , dead : used particularly when speaking of the dead person's actions while alive. ( Generally must be preceded by a possessive or an article , commonly " the "; see usage notes. Can itself only precede the person's name, never follow it. )
examples: Her late husband had left her well provided for.
Mary was entitled to the crown by her late father’s testament.

definitions.definition: Existing or holding some position not long ago, but not now; departed, or gone out of office.
Recent — relative to the noun it modifies.
Of a star or class of stars, cooler than the sun.
